pleasure is resourcing.

as my “Venus in my Aquarius 2nd House & ruling my Taurus 5th House” contemplations reminded me:

pleasure is a resource, and it is also something that resources.

pleasure feeds and soothes the nervous system. pleasure regulates. depending on the source of the pleasure, it also co-regulates, brings us into closer relational connection.

pleasure is not limited to sex or sexual eros; pleasure is also laughter, also scent, also the sonic texture of wind through trees, the sparking delight of a zappingly sweetsour clementine.

pleasure brings us into the present, more or less fully, and by doing so, it brings us a fuel that can be only accessed in the here and now.

when i say resource, i mean something renewable. i mean something exploitable (in the negative sense). i mean something that benefits from our care & stewardship. i mean something that nourishes. i mean something that can flood, and something that can dry up, leaving behind parched soil and leafless trees.

pleasure can be engaged with generously or ascetically. it can be weaponized and withheld. it inspires & enflames; it annihilates & engulfs; it enlivens & propels, a fuel beyond capture.

pleasure is Venusian — and accessing, honoring, sharing, celebrating, delighting within it, without becoming an insatiable ghost?

this is a skill that unlocks the most abundant, most aching, most renewable, most waterfalls-cascading-through-incandescent-rainbows, most ceaselessly relevant, most anti-Puritanical, most exquisite, most constantly-present-if-not-constantly-felt, most simulacquered, and perhaps even the most necessary of resources.

for what is life without Venus’s sweetness?

what is life without even the tiniest, most ephemeral of pleasures?

relational astrology includes looking at the planets as relating with one another.

Mars needs Venus, for one cannot separate (Mars) what is not joined (Venus).

and Venus needs Mars, for one cannot join what isn’t separated.

Jupiter needs Mercury, for grand ideas (Jupiter) come to naught with detail (Mercury).

and Mercury needs Jupiter, for a field of details is pointless without a larger purpose.

the Sun needs Saturn, for there is no center (Sun) without an edge (Saturn).

and Saturn needs the Sun, for there is no periphery without a center.

the Moon needs Saturn, for there is no care (Moon) without containment (Saturn).

and Saturn needs the Moon, for the container needs something to hold.

these combos are all based on the oppositions of the zodiac signs ruled by the planets (following the classical rulership scheme):

Mars rules Aries & Scorpio; Venus rules Libra & Taurus.
Aries is opposite Libra
Scorpio is opposite Taurus.

Jupiter rules Sagittarius & Pisces; Mercury rules Gemini & Virgo.
Sagittarius is opposite Gemini.
Pisces is opposite Virgo.

the Sun rules Leo; Saturn rules Aquarius. 
Leo is opposite Aquarius.

the Moon rules Cancer; Saturn rules Capricorn.
Cancer is opposite Capricorn.

planetary combination & collaboration is absolutely present beyond these sign-based oppositions. it’s an excellent bit of homework to deliberately find the reciprocities between planets — the chart as a dancefloor, not a battlefield.

looking at the planets as collaborators opens up so much more meaning & interpretive agility than only looking at them as rivals. there’s far more harmony amongst them than you might think.

PISCES IS FAITH BEYOND MEASURE

Pisces stereotypes are rooted in a conception of Pisces where it is ruled by the slow-moving outer planet Neptune and attached to the themes of the 12th House.

there are absolutely overlaps and affinities between Pisces, Neptune, and the 12th House. BUT THESE AFFINITIES ARE NOT THE WHOLE STORY.

Pisces is a mutable water sign whose traditional ruler is Jupiter, planet of growth, stability, optimism, generosity, magnanimity, faith, and all of the big-picture things that contribute to life’s sweetness.

mutability means Pisces resists being pinned down, caged, narrowly defined. Pisces facilitates change and transition, taking us from Northern Hemisphere winter towards the thaw of spring. mutability is a quality Pisces shares with Sagittarius, Gemini, and Virgo.

as a water sign, Pisces draws us towards reflection, feeeeeeelings, the flow of living, emotional depths & breadths, the moisture that allows life to spring forth from dry earth. Cancer and Scorpio share in Pisces’s watery nature.

and as a Jupiterian sign? Pisces BELIEVES, and if it doesn’t, it aches towards believing with all its being. Pisces wants to see the best in people, the best in the world. Pisces wants everyone to be included in its oceanic vision. Pisces brings loving unification to the philosophical fire of the other Jupiter-ruled sign, Sagittarius.

what if you stopped pigeonholing Pisces as sleepy crybabies detached from reality and started seeing them as wisdom carriers whose ways of knowing aren’t (generally) conducive to capitalism?

what if you gave Pisces the room it needs to believe instead of dismissing their mutability as incomprehensible?

what if you honored Pisces as spiritually generous instead of using Pisces as an emotional sponge?

what if you gave Jupiter permission to express its stabilizing grace through the potency of water instead of perpetuating the “rational” mistrust & dismissal of the nonlinear?

when allowed to flourish, Pisces is a magnanimous gift that transcends transactionality, a threat to the structures that maintain the falsehood of constructed separation.

what a blessing.

as my yearboss Venus forms a square with my natal Saturn, i’m being reminded of these words i wrote in 2021:

“in a culture that over-glorifies self-martyrdom at the feet of the false gods of capitalist productivity, quite a few of our genuine NEEDS have been shunted into the category of WANTS.
.
at the same time, WANTS have been demoted to the realm of indulgent superfluity, aspects of existence that are unnecessary and therefore INEFFICIENT.
.
capitalism loves efficiency. if (some) WANTS are inefficient, well, it’s not hard to ascertain capitalism’s opinions of them.
.
for example, we have been convinced that art & beauty are wants, not needs.
.
as @thenapministry preaches, we have been convinced that unabashed rest & relaxation are wants, not needs.
.
maybe you think that receiving emotional safety & honesty from the people you’re connected with is a want, not a need.
.
maybe a genuinely comfortable bed is a want, not a need.
.
maybe joy is a want, not a need.
.
maybe love is a want, not a need.
.
on the surface, calling love a mere WANT might seem bonkers.
.
but sit with that for a second.
.
how many times have you behaved as though love — for yourself, for others, from others — is just a want? NBD?
.
and what were the consequences of that?
.
how many friendships, loverships, situationships, kinships, etc. have you allowed to continue because you’ve convinced yourself you don’t “NEED” the qualities of connection you yearn for? how much of your genuine self have you silenced because of that?
.
manipulated WANTS are what keep people consuming far beyond what is generally sustainable but is NEEDED for capitalism to continue its voracious gluttony for the sake of those on top of the heap. our true wants (NEEDS) get buried beneath condition & pernicious advertising that manipulates our needs (WANTS) for acceptance, connection, recognition, entertainment, rest, & even the barest simulacrum of “good enoughness” within a context where our human failings & inefficiencies will always mean we fall short of the mechanistic ideal.

THERE IS NO ASTROLOGY WITHOUT EARTH.
one thing that hardly ever gets discussed when it comes to astrology is the fact that the astrological perspective finds its roots here, on Earth, on this hunk of space rock we all call home.

it’s easy to forget that Earth is a planet. we’re far too close to it to perceive it the way we perceive Mars or Jupiter; most of us do not attend to Earth’s cycles the way we observe Saturn cycles or Mercury’s frenetic triannual retrogrades.

our flesh, bones, and blood are made up of the materials of this place. this place is made up of the same cosmic fairy dust that composes the celestial spheres we turn to in search of answers and insights. 

and those answers and insights we seek?

they mean nothing if our mothership can no longer support the immensity of life She’s been nourishing since far before humans evolved sufficient intelligence to hubristically claim dominance over the rest of nature and even each other.

if you’re an astrologer, astrology student, astrology enthusiast, keep in mind astrology’s inherent Earthly perspective. contemplate what that might mean in terms of your relationships with the planets out there as well as the planet right here.

remember:

every day is Earth Day; this day just happens to be when people & organizations & disingenuous corporations happen to be posting about it.

remember:

there is no astrology, there is no you, there is no me, without Earth.

— gratitude isn’t an inherently easy thing for everyone to experience.

gratitude can feel like a trap.

gratitude to can feel like a weapon in the hand of guilt, an obligatory bludgeon wielded by those who tangle obligation with resentment with care.

gratitude can feel like drowning, an obliteration of the ability to think & speak, a looming threat of evidence that whatever was received was ultimately unearned, undeserved.

if you, like me, have ever struggled with feeling overwhelmed by gratitude, know this:

becoming *able to withstand gratitude* is, in itself, one of the greatest expressions of genuine gratitude there is.

let yourself cultivate the capacity to fully, sincerely, unabashedly appreciate **WITHOUT** anticipating a catch, without looking for the reasons why you don’t deserve or didn’t earn whatever it is.

a secret:

most of the things that you could choose to be grateful for have NOTHING whatsoever to do with your deservingness.

did you earn the oxygen you’re breathing? the bones that prop up your form? the heart that pumps your blood?

see what i mean?
